  "eprint": {
    "title": "Transciphering, using FiLIP and TFHE for an efficient delegation of computation",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Clément Hoffmann",
        "email": "hoffmann@uclouvain",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Pierrick Méaux",
        "email": "meaux@uclouvain",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Thomas Ricosset",
        "email": "ricosset@thalesgroup",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Improved filter permutators are designed to build stream ciphers that\ncan be efficiently evaluated homomorphically. So far the transciphering with\nsuch ciphers has been implemented with homomorphic schemes from the second\ngeneration. In theory the third generation is more adapted for the particular\ndesign of these ciphers. In this article we study how suitable it is in practice. We\nimplement the transciphering of different instances of the stream cipher family\nFiLIP with homomorphic encryption schemes of the third generation using the\nTFHE library.\nWe focus on two kinds of filter for FiLIP. First we consider the direct sum of\nmonomials, already evaluated using HElib and we show the improvements on\nthese results. Then we focus on the XOR-threshold filter, we develop strategies\nto efficiently evaluate any symmetric Boolean function in an homomorphic way,\nallowing us to give the first timings for such filters. We investigate different\napproaches for the homomorphic evaluation: using the leveled homomorphic\nscheme TGSW, an hybrid approach combining TGSW and TLWE schemes, and\nthe gate boostrapping approach. We discuss the costs in time and memory and\nthe impact on delegation of computation of these different approaches, and we\nperform a comparison with others transciphering schemes.",
    "keywords": [
      "Homomorphic Encryption",
      "TFHE",
      "Improved Filter Permutator",
      "Transciphering"
    ],
